{
  "message": "fuzz(por-authenticator): 14 boundary seeds + fix harness overflow\n\nExtends fuzz_por_authenticator from 3 ad-hoc seeds (empty,\nsingle_block, multi_block) to 17 by adding 14 structured seeds that\ntarget boundary states the harness was previously not exploring:\n\n  * key extremes: all-zero, all-FF, sequential 0..32, high-bit only\n  * base_index extremes: u64::MAX and i64::MAX (test the\n    \"verification must bind to its block index\" assertion against\n    wrapping_add(1) overflow)\n  * block-count extremes: 1, 8 (= MAX_BLOCKS), 8 empty, 8 growing\n  * block-size extremes: 0 bytes, 64 bytes, 255 bytes (largest the\n    declared_len: u8 protocol can express), full 0..=254 byte range\n  * realistic mixed: PNG-ish header, JSON, zero fill, ASCII string\n  * adjacency: identical blocks at adjacent indices (must produce\n    distinct authenticators); three blocks differing only in the\n    last byte (must produce distinct authenticators); alternating\n    empty / 1-byte across MAX_BLOCKS slots\n  * 32-byte aligned blocks across MAX_BLOCKS \u2014 typical disk-block\n    authenticator workload\n\nWhile validating the seeds, libFuzzer exposed a real harness defect\nthat had previously gone unnoticed: the per-block index computation\nwas `base_index + offset as u64`, which panics with an arithmetic\noverflow when base_index sits within `MAX_BLOCKS` of u64::MAX. The\nproduction code paths (`compute_authenticator` /\n`verify_authenticator` / `AuthenticatorTable::build`) all accept\narbitrary u64 indices without overflow, so the harness was\nartificially refusing to explore part of the input space.\nReplaced with a `block_index(offset)` closure built on\n`base_index.wrapping_add(offset as u64)`. Validated by a 21-second\nlibFuzzer run: 676 K executions, no crashes.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>",
